english:
  title: Preface to the Collected Works of Master Jeong of Wonjae, Minister of State
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In my youth, I studied under Master Mog-eun, and in those days, many illustrious scholars renowned for their virtue and learning exchanged poems with one another. Among them, Master Jeong of Wonjae and Master Han of Liuxiang were particularly brilliant. The Master praised Jeong for his commanding vigor and abundant eloquence, and Han for his clarity and lofty spirit. Whenever they composed a poem, they would answer one another in turn, accumulating dozens of pieces, each more boundless than the last. Ah, what a glorious age it was! Their friendship grew ever deeper, and they would visit each other almost daily. When they met, they would calmly discuss the Way and righteousness, delighting in gentle harmony, entirely forgetting the hour to depart. I, attending at their side, heard the essence of their discourse and profited greatly. Yet within a few years, both gentlemen and the Master passed away. Now those in office are consumed by worldly affairs and the pursuit of accomplishment, scarcely finding leisure. The echoes of poetic exchange have long fallen silent. Alas, how can we not lament the decline of the poetic tradition and the corruption of true friendship?

    Master Jeong possessed both profound integrity and deeply erudite learning. Early in his career, he rose to prominence in the literary world with great distinction. When he became Remonstrance Officer, the monk Dun of Eagle Peak enjoyed the Emperor's favor, and the Master boldly submitted a memorial denouncing his treachery. For this, he was exiled to the southern frontier, yet continued his moral cultivation with even greater diligence. When Dun was indeed condemned as a traitor, the Master was recalled and reinstated, rising eventually to the office of Chief Minister. During that perilous time when the realm was ruled by a young sovereign and beset with dangers, he labored without regard for himself, resolving the nation's difficulties with integrity and wisdom. Surely his achievements were magnificent.

    His father, Master Seolgok, possessed exceptional moral integrity and profoundest learning, and his poetry reached sublime heights. Though he departed this world too early, the Master inherited and expanded his legacy. His verse possessed commanding force and abundant expression, clarity and radiance—nearly surpassing the light of his predecessor and furnishing an exemplary model for posterity. The Master's two sons also inherited the literary tradition, both becoming founding merit subjects of our glorious dynasty. Their literary excellence and vigorous expression faithfully preserve the family's established principles. The elder brother, whose name was Jong, went on a diplomatic mission to China and never returned; he was posthumously titled Minister of Culture and Compassion, leaving behind several manuscript volumes. The younger brother, whose name was Tak, is now the Lord of Qingcheng and serves with me as Companion to the Heir Apparent. Now that the Collected Works of Wonjae is being published, I am asked to write this preface. Having witnessed the splendid gatherings of earlier worthies in literary discourse, I lament the decline of the poetic tradition in our own time. Yet I rejoice in the Master's family, which continues to inherit both literary achievement and worldly virtue. Thus I write this preface.
  footnotes:
    - Master Mog-eun (牧隱) refers to Yi Saek (1328-1396), a renowned Neo-Confucian scholar and teacher of great influence in late Goryeo
    - The monk Dun (旽) was a corrupt Buddhist monk who wielded significant political influence during the Goryeo period before being executed for treason
    - The reference to 'eagle peak' (鷲城) is associated with Buddhist monasteries and their political machinations
